<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910424-0101</DOCNO><DOCID>910424-0101.</DOCID><HL>   International:   BBC Brown Boveri   Says Fritz Leutiler   To Quit as Chairman   ----   A Wall Street Journal Roundup</HL><DATE>03/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9</SO><CO>   ASEAY S.ABB WNEWS Z.BBB</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)EARNINGS (ERN)DIVIDENDS (DIV)</IN><LP>   BBC Brown Boveri AG, the Swiss parent of engineering giantABB Asea Brown Boveri Ltd., said Fritz Leutwiler plans tostep down as its chairman and also relinquish the post of ABBco-chairman next year.   His successor will be David de Pury, 48 years old,currently Switzerland's ambassador to the General Agreementon Tariffs and Trade talks.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Leutwiler, 67 years old and a former president of theSwiss central bank, became chairman of the Brown Boveri Groupin 1985. He launched a reorganization that culminated in thestunning merger with arch-rival Asea in 1987 to form one ofthe world's biggest electrical engineering concerns.   Separately, BBC said its consolidated 1990 net income,excluding third party interest, fell 17% to 417 million Swissfrancs ($294.2 million).   ABB Asea Brown Boveri said profit was little changed in1990, despite a 30% rise in group sales. Results fell shortof analysts' estimates. The company also said earnings couldbe flat this year.   Meanwhile, the Swedish parent, Asea AB, announced detailsof the long-awaited spinoff of its non-ABB assets under a newcompany, Nybroviken AB, to be quoted separately on theStockholm Stock Exchange.   Asea AB also released earnings. Its pretax profit inchedup a mere 1.8%. Profit declined at ABB's industrysegmentmainly because of hefty restructuring costs at U.S.unit Combustion Engineering Inc., which was acquired in late1989. ABB said it is slowing the pace of acquisitions.</TEXT></DOC>